The <a href="https://www.ccr.ro/en">Constitutional Court of Romania</a> [official website] <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/europe/romania-court-same-sex-couples-should-have-legal-protection/2018/09/28/d05c702c-c31a-11e8-9451-e878f96be19b_story.html?noredirect=on&amp;utm_term=.8983c3149645">ruled </a>[WASH POST report] on Friday that homosexual couples are entitled to the same familial rights as heterosexual couples, and should therefore benefit from the same "legal and juridical recognition of their rights and obligations."

The ruling precedes the <a href="/news/2018/09/romania-high-court-approves-referendum-that-may-impede-legalization-of-same-sex-marriage/">national referendum</a> [JURIST report]scheduled for October 6-7, which may make the legalization of same-sex marriage in Romania more difficult. The referendum seeks to redefine the term "family" in <a href="http://www.cdep.ro/pls/dic/site.page?den=act2_2&amp;par1=2#t2c2s0sba48">Article 48</a> [text] of the Romanian constitution from a "freely consent marriage of the spouses" to "a union between a man and a woman".

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

On Wednesday, a judge from the District Court of Montana <a href="https://www.splcenter.org/sites/default/files/documents/order_on_motion_to_dismiss.pdf">denied a motion to dismiss on a suit</a> alleging that the publisher of the neo-Nazi site Daily Stormer coordinated an online campaign of harassment against a Jewish real estate agent because of First Amendment protections. On December 16, 2016, the Daily Stormer publisher, Andrew Anglin published a string of articles calling for readers to attack Tanya Gersh. Articles that were titled: "Let'sHit Em Up[.] Are y'all ready for an old fashioned Troll Storm? Because A YO-- it's that time, fam.

The online harassment "targeted  [Gersh], and Anglin published Gersh's phone numbers, email addresses, and social media profiles, as well as those of her husband, twelve-year-old son, friends, and colleagues. Anglin asked readers to "Tell them you are sickened by their Jew agenda to attack and harm the mother of someone whom they disagree with."

"United States Magistrate Judge Jeremiah C. Lynch entered his Findings and Recommendation in this case on May 3, 2018, recommending that Defendant Andrew Anglin's Motion to Dismiss be denied to the extent it seeks dismissal."

Judge Lynch had found that the Jewish real estate agent, Tanya Gersh's loss of privacy and ability to practice her religion due to the harassment created separate claims. The judge found that there were three adequately stated claims "under Montana law for invasion of privacy, intentional infliction of emotional distress, and violations of the Anti-Intimidation Act."

