This Wednesday, the International Criminal Court's Chief Prosecutor Fatou Bensouda issued a <a href="https://www.icc-cpi.int/Pages/item.aspx?name=181017-otp-stat-palestine" target="_blank" rel="noopener">statement</a> cautioning Israel against proceeding with the forced evacuation of Khan al-Ahmar, a Bedouin settlement within an Israeli-controlled area of West Bank.<span>. </span>

The Chief Prosecutor's warning followed the Israeli Supreme Court's <a href="https://supremedecisions.court.gov.il/Home/Download?path=HebrewVerdicts%5C18%5C930%5C051%5Ce09&amp;fileName=18051930.E09&amp;type=2">rejection of petitions </a>to halt the demolition of <a href="https://www.hrw.org/news/2018/09/16/demolition-palestinian-community-imminent">Khan al-Ahmar.</a> The Israeli authorities have engaged in a <a href="https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2018/09/israel-opt-israeli-court-approves-a-war-crime-by-ruling-in-favour-of-demolishing-the-entire-village-of-khan-al-ahmar/">protracted effort</a> to demolish the village over the past ten years.

Chief Prosecutor Bensouda warned that Israel's actions could be classified as war crimes under the <a href="https://www.icc-cpi.int/resourcelibrary/official-journal/rome-statute.aspx">Rome Statute</a>, which prohibits<span> "</span>extensive destruction of property without military necessity and population transfers in an occupied territory."

Chief Prosecutor Bensouda indicated that she and her Office would be closely following the violence on either side of the <a href="https://www.hrw.org/middle-east/n-africa/israel/palestine">longstanding conflict</a> between Israel and Palestine and will intervene if necessary as appropriate.

